                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d733">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">110.11 DU/6–1254: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-12T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 12, 1954—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 175. Repeated information Paris 423.
                        <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> told me yesterday Communists
                    could not accept Colombo Powers for Indochinese Supervisory Commission. He asked
                    what was “minimum” US position. I reaffirmed that US could not accept “50–50”
                    composition, that Laos and Cambodia must be treated separately, and that we
                    could not associate ourselves with any form of capitulation on principle in
                    Indochina.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
